'''El Hassan El-Abbassi''' (born 13 April 1984)<ref name=IAAF>[http://www.iaaf.org/athletes/bahrain/el-hassan-elabbassi-261866#progression El Hassan Elabbassi]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref><ref>[http://www.incheon2014ag.org/Sports/Biographies/Athletes_Profile/?ParticCode=5104216&lang=en ELABBASSI Elhassan]. Incheon2014AG. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> is a [[Morocco|Moroccan]]-born [[long-distance runner]] who competes internationally for [[Bahrain]]. He was the gold medallist in the [[10,000 metres]] at the [[2014 Asian Games]]. He has a personal best of 27:32.96 minutes for that distance.

==Career==
El-Abbassi initially ran in [[middle-distance running|middle-distance]] events but a move up to longer distances brought him his first successes.<ref name=Tilas>[http://www.tilastopaja.org/db/atm.php?ID=127800&Season=2011&Odd=0 El Hassan El Abbassi]. Tilastopaja. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> In his debut over the distance, he set a personal best of 62:53 minutes at the 2011 [[Marrakesh Half Marathon]]. His first race abroad followed in February and he was the surprise winner at the [[Eurocross]] [[cross country running|cross country]] meet.<ref>Wenig, J<U+00F6>rg (2011-02-27). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/jamal-and-moroccan-men-dominate-in-diekirch Jamal and Moroccan men dominate in Diekirch]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> An outing at the [[Corrida de Langueux]] [[10K run]] brought him fourth place.<ref>Vazel, Pierre-Jean (2011-06-24). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/tsegay-and-wangari-take-langueux-10km-titles Tsegay and Wangari take Langueux 10Km titles]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> He had three further outings over the [[half marathon]] distance that year and was in the top three each time: he was runner-up in [[Zwolle Half Marathon|Zwolle]], set a personal best of 61:13 minutes for third at the [[Route du Vin Half Marathon]], and was under 62 minutes again to win at the [[Zhuhai Half Marathon]] in China that December. He failed to progress much further in 2012, with a podium finish at the [[Yangzhou Half Marathon]] and and fourth at the [[Philadelphia Distance Run]] being his best races abroad. However, he did win his first national title over [[10,000 metres]] with a personal best time of 28:12.40 minutes.<ref name=Tilas/>

El-Abbassi established himself among the world's [[road running]] elite in 2013. In January he set a new best of 61:09 minutes over the half marathon in [[Marrakesh]].<ref name=Tilas/> His best run that year was in an event almost half that distance: at the [[Ottawa 10K]] in Canada he won in a lifetime best of 27:37 minutes, beating Kenya's [[Geoffrey Mutai]] and ranking sixth globally that year as a result.<ref>Gains, Paul (2013-05-26). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/double-moroccan-victories-in-ottawa-10km Double Moroccan victories in Ottawa 10km]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref><ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/road-running/10-kilometres/outdoor/men/senior/2013 10 Kilometres - men - senior - outdoor - 2013]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> He also had a sub-28-minute race at the [[Casablanca 10K]] one week later.<ref name=Tilas/>

He decided to start running for Bahrain and formally requested a [[list of eligibility transfers in athletics|transfer of allegiance]] in August 2013. He became eligible to compete for his new nation in July 2014.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/download/download?filename=b18c2081-a442-436f-95ff-30eebf5955cf.pdf&urlslug=Transfer%20of%20Allegiance%20-%202014%20-%20as%20officially%20announced%20in%20the%20IAAF%20Newsletter 2014  TRANSFER OF ALLEGIANCE as officially announced in the IAAF Newsletter]. IAAF (2014-09-30). Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> He set two [[track running|track]] bests in the 2014 season: first a time of 13:33.95 minutes for the [[500 metres]] at the [[Rabat Meeting]] then a 27:32.96-minute best over the 10,000&nbsp;m at the [[Prefontaine Classic]].<ref name=IAAF/> The latter time ranked him eleventh in the world that year and the second fastest non-Kenyan after world-leader [[Galen Rupp]].<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/middlelong/10000-metres/outdoor/men/senior/2014 10,000 Metres - men - senior - outdoor - 2014]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref> His international debut for Bahrain was at the [[Athletics at the 2014 Asian Games|2014 Asian Games]]. Running in the 10,000&nbsp;m he held the lead and beat [[Suguru Osako]] to the line to win the gold medal <U+2013> maintaining Bahrain's dominance for a third straight edition.<ref>Mulkeen, Jon (2014-10-02). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/asian-games-2014-incheon-javelin-china Two Asian records broken on fantastic day for China at the Asian Games]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-10-03.</ref>

